value.0: The grey hair seems out of place on this well-built frame, particularly amongst the myriad of tattoos adorning what flesh you see.
A mild, but steady flow of water pours down from a slight crack in the ceiling of the cave, dissapearing into a metal grate in the floor.
You have found a secret grate. This is bound to lead somewhere interesting.
Scraps of worn rope indicate this wooden post may once have supported a rope-bridge, long since rotted away, likely from the flooding tides.

Only a single page remains readable in this book, which appears to be the log from some sailing vessel. 

The page reads as follows:

Three days out of Wiltun, and we've run afoul of a terrible storm. We're riding her out as best we can, but already two crewmen have been washed overboard, never to be seen again. A sad, lonely way to be meeting yer end, deep-sixed to Davy Jones' Locker.
Half buried in sand, a chest has temporarily washed ashore. At least until the tides pull it back to sea once again.

A wheelbarrow. 

Though mostly rotten from the wetness of the cave, this is evidence that perhaps the narrow twists and turns of the cave are not as natural as they might seem.

Why would someone want to carve out tunnels in a sea cave?

The bow of the rowboat has been smashed in by the rocks, the remains half-sunk, saved from dissapearing under the waves only by the rope tying it to the shore. How it came to rest here is anyones guess.
The chain disappears into some unseen recess above you where it presumably activates some hidden mechanism.

At the back end of this dark recess in the wall, is the sliding wall panel used to get in here. 

A small lever appears to open it from this side, though a complicated series of gears and counterweights seems designed to automatically reclose the secret entrance within moments of pulling the lever.

Umberlee's Dogma: The sea is a savage place, and those that travel it had best be willing to pay the price of challenging Umberlee's domain. All should know the Bitch Queen and fear her, for the wind and the wave can reach everywhere if sufficiently angered. Fair offerings bring fair winds to sea travelers, but those that do not pay their respects will find that the sea is as cold as Umberlee's heart. Spread the word of the might of Umberlee, and let no service be done in her name without a price. Make folk fear the wind and wave unless a cleric of umberlee is there to protect them. Slay those who ascribe sea and shore storms to Talos.
